posts.name: Jainish Patel
posts.cooked: Which one is better and what are the added benefits, etc.?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked:
I assume you’re talking about the holonomic drive controller in PathPlannerLib. Ramsete is for controlling nonholonomic drivetrains (e.g., differential drive, which can’t move sideways).

If you have a holonomic drivetrain like swerve, use a holonomic controller instead of Ramsete because you’d be giving up a degree of freedom otherwise.

posts.name: Jainish Patel
posts.cooked: I am talking about the Ramsete controller in PathPlannerLib

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: Could you link to it? I only found pathplanner/pathplannerlib/src/main/java/com/pathplanner/lib/controllers at main · mjansen4857/pathplanner · GitHub yesterday, which just has the holonomic controller.

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: PPRamseteCommand just uses RamseteController as-is. It’s a PathPlannerTrajectory version of RamseteCommand.

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: In that case, the better comparison would be RamseteCommand vs PPRamseteCommand. The latter has better integration with PathPlanner’s trajectory library.

posts.name: Alex Tsekhansky
posts.cooked: We found PathPlanner with its own trajectory build tool MUCH easier to use than Ramsete with PathWeaver. We also stay with the tank drive this year. We tested most of the fancy things PathPlanner does, including on-the-fly trajectory generation, with good results. The most important task for us was to gain precise understanding of every single parameter used for the command, its implication on a trajectory navigation, as well as the method of obtaining it (e.g. from SysID). I found this year’s SysID much more stable than the one from prior years and producing good results (our characterization was reasonably matching predicted/simulated values on the graph). If you will have specific questions about it, I may have answers for you
